data.text:
MELBOURNE PREVIEW EXHIBITION

1130 High St. Armadale

17 August - 20 August, 10am to 4pm

SYDNEY PREVIEW EXHIBITION

97-99 Queen St. Woollahra

24 August - 28 August, 10am to 4pm

The Wrobel Collection Part II: A Celebration of Life and Leisure

Following on from the success of The Fred and Elinor Wrobel Collection: A Curated Salon in April, Bonhams is delighted to present The Fred and Elinor Wrobel Collection: The Artist's Eye. With a focus on landscapes, scenes of the harbour and beach life, boating, and his adoptive home of Australia, many of the works had particular significance for Fred. His earliest memory of Sydney was his arrival by ship to Woolloomooloo Wharf after the war as a Holocaust survivor from Poland. Woolloomooloo features in two works: Julian Ashton's The Butler Stairs, Woolloomooloo (lot 21) and Sali Herman's Woolloomooloo Art Gallery, 1988 (lot 34) - the gallery that Fred and Elinor established on Nicholson Street in 1983.

Fred's heart was deeply tied to his adoptive city's magnificent harbour. Adrian Feint, a favoured artist, captured its splendour with his jewel-like, richly coloured view with the iconic bridge in the background in Sydney Harbour, Scene from a Garden (lot 6). As Joanna Mendelssohn recounts in Fred's 2015 Sydney Morning Herald obituary, the Wrobels never lived far from the water and Fred was to become an accomplished boat builder and yachtsman as well as an avid competitor in yacht races. His passion soon became a fully-fledged business when he purchased Elizabeth Bay Marine Services. As well as managing the marina, the business also offered boat sales, rigging and servicing. Of particular note on the boating theme is Roy de Maistre's St Jean de Luz, 1931 (lot 31). Set in his beloved French seaside town, the work highlights the artist's skill with form and colour as well as his interest in perspective in his depiction of brightly coloured vessels stored away for the day.

The Wrobels' astute eye and considered approach and their continuing support of women artists led them to two of the most important acquisitions in the collection: Grace Cossington Smith's Thanksgiving Service, 1945-46 (lot 10) and Hilda Rix Nicholas' Children at Mount Annan, Holbrook (lot 40). Each of these works are closely related to important paintings, both held in the collection of the Queensland Art Gallery, Brisbane. Each is focused on Australian life of the period - Thanksgiving Service, 1945-46 reflecting on life following the end of the war and Children at Mount Annan, Holbrook relates to the often-overlooked role of females on the land.
